\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Friendly House, Inc. (Phoenix, AZ)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Friendly House, Inc. is a social service agency whose mission is to eliminate illiteracy among Hispanics. It is dedicated to the betterment of immigrants who \b \i0 \ul0 [*62]\b0 \i0 \ul0   reside in the South Phoenix area. Friendly House offers the following programs: immigration assistance, education, social services/counseling, youth programs, home/personal care, rehabilitation, information and referral services, and parenting skills training. In collaboration with NCLR'S C<2>E<2> program, Friendly House operates after school academic enrichment programs for elementary and junior high school students and education and literacy programs for their parents. Although the majority of its clients are of Hispanic origin, Friendly House offers its services to anyone in need.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Greater Dallas Foundation, Inc. (Dallas, TX)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1981, the Greater Dallas Foundation, Inc. is a private, nonprofit corporation organized to facilitate the provision of legal assistance to underprivileged people who are unable to afford the services of a private attorney. The Foundation works primarily to link disadvantaged clients with private attorneys, who are encouraged to take significant cases with the associated costs and/or legal fees underwritten by the Foundation. Community development activities are a new focus of the Foundation, which will work in housing, business, and \b \i0 \ul0 [*63]\b0 \i0 \ul0   community development. The Foundation also provides advocacy and youth leadership training.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Guadalupe Center, Inc. (GCI) (Kansas City, MO)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 GCI is a community-based organization which seeks to serve the needs of the elderly, youth, and other residents of the Westside community, as well as Hispanics throughout the Kansas City metropolitan area. It provides comprehensive services including education, elderly services, day care, teen pregnancy services, recreation, and employment and training. It operates an alternative high school and helps operate a neighborhood parochial elementary school. In collaboration with NCLR's C<2>E<2> program, GCI offers an Academia del Pueblo program for elementary school students and adult education activities for their families.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Hispanic American Council, Inc. (Kalamazoo, MI)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1982, the Hispanic American Council, Inc. strives to advocate for the Hispanic population in southwest Michigan and to nourish and encourage their diverse cultural heritage within the larger community. The Council seeks to assist Hispanics in maintaining self-sufficiency and fostering social and economic well-being by concentrating on education,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*64]\b0 \i0 \ul0   employment, and housing. Its services include immigration assistance, English-as-a-Second-Language (Family Reading Program), court interpretation, emergency interpretation, health referrals, food referrals, clothing, job placement, resume preparation, and housing referrals.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Hispanic Coalition (Miami, FL)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Hispanic Coalition's purpose is to promote the unification and active participation of Hispanic organizations in Miami, to enable them to voice their needs and concerns in order to receive equal economic, social, political, and cultural benefits in the State of Florida. It provides community development, educational, professional/career development, employment and training, immigration services, and information and referral services.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Housing for Mesa, Inc. (Mesa, AZ)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1988, Housing for Mesa, Inc. is a nonprofit, community-based housing development corporation that promotes the creation and preservation of permanent, affordable housing and provides housing support services for low-income families and individuals with children. Housing for Mesa has created a private/public partnership in which public resources, such as local Community Development \b \i0 \ul0 [*65]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Block Grants and state funds, are leveraged to bring in additional private resources and in-kind contributions from the community, including participation by local lending institutions. Current housing programs include: First-Time Homebuyer Program; substantial rehabilitation of existing homeownership housing units; and housing information and counseling services.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Houston Community Services (Houston, TX)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Houston Community Services was incorporated in 1975 with three primary missions: to operate a social service center, to provide cultural enrichment, and to carry out economic development. It provides a variety of services to the community, including notary, income tax preparation, immigration services, and referral to jobs and other agencies in the Hispanic barrio of Houston.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Humanidad, Inc. (Rocky Hill, CT)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1980, Humanidad, Inc. is a nonprofit agency which provides bilingual/bicultural educational and residential services, as well as advocacy and health care for persons with disabilities. Its services include residential management, nursing, educational, life domain and behavioral programs for person with developmental disabilities. Humanidad \b \i0 \ul0 [*66]\b0 \i0 \ul0   maintains five independent community residential homes in the greater Hartford region, each serving a small number of clients. Direct care is provided 24 hours a day by more than 30 full-time and part-time employees and contractors.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 La Causa, Inc. (Milwaukee, WI)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Incorporated in 1972, La Causa, Inc. serves over 4,000 children, adults, and families each year. La Causa's services include a Pre-College Education Center for adults, Family Resource Center, Learnfare, Parental and Family Responsibility consortium, Crisis Nursery, Satellite Homes, Nurturing Program, Respite for Special Needs Children, day care, Head Start, kindergarten, Hispanic Early Learning Program, and foster care.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Latin American Professional Women's Association (LAPWA) (Los Angeles, CA)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 LAPWA, which originated from the Los Angeles Bilingual Secretaries Association in 1975, provides a mutual support group for Latinas working to enrich themselves vocationally, educationally, and culturally. It achieves this through different programs, such as a scholarship fund for Latinas who are heads of household over the age of 25 and in college; a "Hermanita/Little Sisters Program," a project that matches \b \i0 \ul0 [*67]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Latina "Big Sister" companions with young Latinas; and a series of educational and informative speakers.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Latin Americans for Social and Economic Development, Inc. (LA SED) (Detroit, MI)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1969, LA SED promotes social and economic development of the Hispanic community and all residents of Southwest Detroit. It provides employment and training, weatherization/energy information and referral, educational services and advocacy, as well as senior citizen and youth services. LA SED sponsors and coordinates an annual "Yuletide Fiesta" which supplies food, toys, and clothing to the needy during the Christmas season.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Latino Family Services (Detroit, MI)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Latino Family Services is an organization that provides a wide range of family and youth services to Latinos and other residents of the Hispanic barrio of Detroit. It operates a substance abuse center, and provides alcohol/drug counseling, AIDS education and testing, counseling and referral, therapeutic and support groups, and in-school and summer youth prevention activities.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 LEARN, Inc. Educational Talent Search (Lubbock, TX)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 LEARN, Inc. Educational Talent Search is an organization designed \b \i0 \ul0 [*68]\b0 \i0 \ul0   to assist individuals who have academic potential to enter or re-enter programs of secondary and post-secondary education. LEARN's participants come from many cultural backgrounds and span a wide range from youth to the elderly. Its services include counseling students about vocational, academic, and career choices; helping in the application process for admissions; ACT and SAT registration; and housing and financial aid.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Mexican American Commission (Lincoln, NE)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Mexican American Commission is a statewide Governor-appointed Board whose mission is to advocate on behalf of the Hispanic community within the State of Nebraska in the areas of employment, health, education, housing, welfare, social adjustment, and other conditions pertaining to the general welfare of Hispanics. The Commission closely follows legislation in Nebraska to promote favorable laws and to oppose laws detrimental to the Hispanic community.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 The Mexican Community Committee of South Chicago (MCC) (Chicago, IL)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1959, MCC offers educational programs, counseling, organized sports, and cultural activities in order to enhance the well being of the youth and families of Southeast \b \i0 \ul0 [*69]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Chicago. By providing advocacy programs with youth-serving agencies in the community, MCC works actively to prevent juvenile delinquency. MCC also offers job development, bilingual educational support, a dropout prevention program, and extensive family counseling. MCC encourages community residents to volunteer in agency programs to promote pride in the community.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 NAF Multicultural Human Development, Inc. (NAF) (North Platte, NE)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1979, NAF is a statewide organization that serves communities in 93 Nebraska counties with the purpose of promoting economic self-sufficiency, social, and physical well-being. Through its seven regional offices, NAF provides services which include: Adult Basic Education (includes English-as-a-Second-Language and GED preparation); vocational/occupational training; on-the-job training; counseling and referrals to employment; supportive and emergency services; outreach to and health services for migrants, seasonal farmworkers, and low-income women and children; HIV/AIDS and substance abuse education and prevention; advocacy and translation; and assistance with family immigration benefits.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 National Asian Pacific Center on Aging\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 [*70]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0  (NAPCA) (Seattle, WA)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 NAPCA represents Asian/Pacific Islander elders at the national level, preparing policy recommendations to improve awareness, access, and utilization of services. In addition, NAPCA networks with Asian/Pacific Islander community-based service providers and mainstream aging organizations to enhance the capabilities of Asian Pacific communities to meet the needs of their elderly through strong formal and informal support.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Northwest Communities Education Center (NCEC) (Granger, WA)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 NCEC is a minority community-based organization which focuses its efforts on responding to the cultural, educational, and informational isolation of the Hispanic/Latino and other disadvantaged communities. NCEC, through its radio station, produces radio programming to help such communities overcome barriers of illiteracy, language, discrimination, poverty, and illness.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 El Proyecto del Barrio, Inc. (Arleta, CA)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1970, El Proyecto del Barrio, Inc. is a nonprofit organization providing bilingual/bicultural comprehensive community services and advocacy in the areas of: drug/alcohol prevention and treatment; job training and employment; primary health \b \i0 \ul0 [*71]\b0 \i0 \ul0   care; and education. The primary target population is Latino and other economically disadvantaged youth and adults in the San Fernando Valley. El Proyecto's programs and services include: health education, family health care clinics, a prenatal service center, youth services, an early intervention program, an outpatient drug free program, a community resource center, and an employment and training program.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Rural Opportunities, Inc. (Rochester, NY)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Rural Opportunities, Inc., is a multistate, nonprofit corporation, organized in 1969 to provide services to and advocate on behalf of migrant and seasonal farmworkers and rural disadvantaged individuals. Its mission is the improvement of the lives and living conditions of its constituency through self-help and advocacy. Rural Opportunities, Inc. offers programs in adult employment, health and safety services, affordable housing development, business and economic development, children and youth services, participant support, advocacy, and employer assistance programs.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Servicios de La Raza. Inc. (Denver, CO)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Servicios de La Raza, Inc., established in 1972, is a state-licensed, bilingual, human services organization.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*72]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Its mission is to provide and advocate for comprehensive, culturally-relevant human services for the Spanish-speaking population of Denver, Colorado. Mental health, alcohol treatment, youth development, employment training, and a variety of basic emergency services are provided in an integrated, comprehensive manner.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Southwest Key Program (Austin, TX)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1987, the Southwest Key Program is a private, nonprofit agency which operates 23 community-based treatment programs for delinquent youth and their families in major cities across Texas and Arizona. It has designed and implemented innovative program models for federal, state, and local agencies, and currently operates seven different program models. Programs include an outreach and tracking program; day treatment; residential treatment centers; in-home services for abused and neglected youth; a program for runaways; a family preservation program; and a program which provides services to delinquent youth and their families from the time they are incarcerated in state institutions to their eventual release to standard parole.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Spanish Speaking Council of Reading and Berks County (Reading, PA)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Spanish \b \i0 \ul0 [*73]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Speaking Council of Reading and Berks County, founded in 1977, serves the needs of the low-income and Hispanic community of Reading and Berks County in Pennsylvania. The center is a multiservice provider striving to promote individual self-sufficiency, a strong family, and a cohesive community by providing programs such as education; support for the elderly; an escort service; housing rehabilitation; drug education; AIDS prevention education; child abuse advocacy; youth violence prevention; and presentations through radio (La Voz Latina) and television (Hispanic Center Presents).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Spanish Theater Repertory Co., Ltd. (Repertorio Espanol) (New York, NY)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1968, Repertorio Espanol serves as a catalyst for cultural exchange between Spanish-speaking and English-speaking Americans, as well as between the United States and its nearest neighbors, by bringing theater to a broad audience in New York City and across the country. Repertoro Espanol offers the best of Latin American, Spanish, and Hispanic-American theater in distinctive, quality productions while working to create a professional company of actors, singers, musicians, and directors who perform in the Spanish \b \i0 \ul0 [*74]\b0 \i0 \ul0   language.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Sparks Housing Development Corporation (El Paso, TX)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1979, Sparks Housing Development Corporation is a community organization made up of residents of the Sparks colonia. The organization represents residents in their efforts to improve living conditions by getting water, electric, and other services to the area. Sparks also assists residents who do not speak or understand English with needs such as applications for services.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Student Alternatives Program, Inc. (San Antonio, TX)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1990, Student Alternatives Program, Inc. is a nonprofit organization which plans, develops, and implements curriculum and instructional services for at-risk and dropout youth from the ages of 14-21 through performance-based contracts with school districts in the State of Texas. The curriculum includes the essential elements required for students to attain their high school diploma from the participating school districts. GED instruction is also provided. The organization has 24 instructional centers throughout the state, representing 28 school districts.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Tejano Center for Community Concerns, Inc. (TCCC) (Houston, TX)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1992, TCCC \b \i0 \ul0 [*75]\b0 \i0 \ul0   is a community-based, nonprofit agency whose mission is to improve opportunities for Hispanics through the provision of educational, social, housing, and economic development initiatives. It operates youth violence prevention programs, ABC/ESL classes, drug abuse and AIDS prevention, and gang intervention and prevention. TCCC is also developing a foster care group home and shelter, organizing resident and homeowner groups, and beginning a home ownership program for low-income families. Ten single family homes were built in 1995 and 50 single family units are projected for 1996. The newest initiative of TCCC is the Raul Yzaguirre Charter School for Success, which targets Hispanic 7th and 8th grade students and will feature one of the most creative and individualized education programs for middle school youth in the country.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Texas Enterprise for Housing Development, Inc. (TEHDI) (Mission, TX)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 TEHDI was incorporated in 1991 to develop affordable housing programs in the South Texas area. TEHDI develops multi-family units for very low-income families through the acquisition of Resolution Trust Corporation single family units, and generating new multi-family units. TEHDI also \b \i0 \ul0 [*76]\b0 \i0 \ul0   sponsors an affordable home ownership program for low-income families.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Valle del Sol, Inc. (Phoenix, AZ)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1970, Valle del Sol's mission is to empower its community through advocacy and a continuum of culturally sensitive health services, partnerships, and social services. Programs include substance abuse prevention and treatment, and a wide range of counseling services for youth and families. Valle del Sol is the founder of the Hispanic Leadership Institute of Phoenix, now operating in partnership with Arizona State University. Valle del Sol also helps provide medical services in conjunction with local hospitals.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Washington Alliance for Immigrant and Refugee Justice (Seattle, WA)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Washington Alliance for Immigrant and Refugee Justice is an alliance of community-based organizations and individuals dedicated to upholding human and civil rights for all immigrants and refugees. The Alliance pursues its mission through community empowerment, public education, political advocacy, and direct action. The work of the Alliance is guided by a nine-member steering committee, which includes representatives of community-based, labor, religious, student, educational,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*77]\b0 \i0 \ul0   social service, and legal advocacy organizations.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Westside Housing Organization (WHO) (Kansas City, MO)\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Founded in 1973, WHO is a nonprofit community development corporation whose mission is to provide decent, safe, and affordable housing in the Westside. WHO programs have included substantial and moderate rehabilitation, minor and emergency repairs, energy conservation improvements, a tool lending library, contractor assistance and referrals, and technical assistance on repairs for residents. WHO has been involved in the community as a local rental manager for over 13 years, and is also involved in the development, ownership, and management of rental properties.
\par 
